trans-unit.source: Animates the value of a <xref href="System.Windows.Media.Media3D.Quaternion"></xref> property between two target values using linear interpolation over a specified <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.Duration*>.
An animation updates the value of a property over a period of time.

An animation effect can be subtle, such as moving a <xref:System.Windows.Shapes.Shape> a few pixels left and right, or dramatic, such as enlarging an object to 200 times its original size while spinning it and changing its color.
To create an animation in [!INCLUDE[TLA#tla_winclient](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md)], you associate an animation with an object's property value.
Target Values The QuaternionAnimation class creates a transition between two target values.

To set its target values, use its <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A>, and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> properties.

The following table summarizes how the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A>, and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> properties may be used together or separately to determine an animation's target values.

|Properties specified|Resulting behavior| |--------------------------|------------------------| |<xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A>|The animation progresses from the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> property to the base value of the property being animated or to a previous animation's output value, depending on how the previous animation is configured.| |<xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A>|The animation progresses from the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> property to the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A> property.| |<xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A>|The animation progresses from the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> property to the value specified by the sum of the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> properties.| |<xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A>|The animation progresses from the animated property's base value or a previous animation's output value to the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A> property.| |<xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A>|The animation progresses from the base value of the property being animated or a previous animation's output value to the sum of that value and the value specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> property.| > [!NOTE] > If you set both the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> properties, the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A> property takes precedence and the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> property is ignored.
To use other interpolation methods or animate between more than two target values, use a <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimationUsingKeyFrames> object.
For information about applying multiple animations to a single property, see [Key-Frame Animations Overview](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).

Freezable Features Because the QuaternionAnimation class inherits from <xref:System.Windows.Freezable>, QuaternionAnimation objects gain several special features, which include the following: they can be declared as , shared among multiple objects, made read-only to improve performance, cloned, and made thread-safe.
For more information about the different features provided by <xref:System.Windows.Freezable> objects, see the [Freezable Objects Overview](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).

Calculates a value that represents the current value of the property being animated, as determined by the <xref href="System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation"></xref>.

If the `defaultOriginValue` is the first in the composition chain, this value will be the snapshot value (if one is available) or the base property value; otherwise this value will be the value returned by the previous animation in the chain with an <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.AnimationClock> that is not <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Clock.Stopped%2A>.

The `defaultDestinationValue` is the base value if the animation is in the first composition layer of animations on a property; otherwise the value is the output value from the previous composition layer of animations for the property.
The suggested origin value, used if the animation does not have its own explicitly set start value.
The suggested destination value, used if the animation does not have its own explicitly set end value.

An <xref href="System.Windows.Media.Animation.AnimationClock"></xref> that generates the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Clock.CurrentTime*> or <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Clock.CurrentProgress*> used by the animation.
The calculated value of the property, as determined by the current animation.
Gets or sets a value that indicates whether the target property's current value should be added to this animation's starting value.

If the animation has only one of its <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.From%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.To%2A>, or <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.QuaternionAnimation.By%2A> properties set, setting this property has no effect.

Gets or sets a value that specifies whether the animation's value accumulates when it repeats.

When this property is set to `true`, the animation's output values only accumulate when the animation's <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Timeline.RepeatBehavior%2A> property causes it to repeat its simple duration.
It does not accumulate its values when it restarts because its parent repeated or because its clock was restarted from a <xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.ClockController.Begin%2A> call.
